-- 
Oil Volatility Rises as Futures Fluctuate on Supply, Economy

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-09-08T17:08:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-08/oil-volatility-rises-as-futures-fluctuate-on-supply-economy.html
Oil options volatility increased as
the underlying futures swung between gains and losses on global
economic concern and after the Energy Department reported that
inventories fell almost twice as much as expected last week.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 42.3 percent at noon in  New York ,
up from 40.1 percent yesterday and 36.5 percent a week ago.  Oil for October delivery rose 47 cents to $89.81 a barrel
at 1 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Prices have
fallen 0.9 percent this year. The futures traded as high as
$90.23 and as low as $88.59 today.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
October $85 puts, with 3,152 lots changing hands. The options
slipped 9 cents to 75 cents a barrel. December $95 calls, the
next-most active contract, gained 25 cents to $4.02 with 2,038
lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  December $100 calls were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 5,969 lots changing hands. They rose
74 cents to $2.11 a barrel. The next-most-active options,
December $75 puts, dropped 64 cents to $1.99 a barrel on volume
of 4,759.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
49,716 contracts. Next were December $70 puts with 46,243 and
December $50 puts with 43,285.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in Dallas at 
